t doesn't close it afterwards. This can lead to source leaks, especially since the stream isn't closed in `ManifestResources.iterator`. It seems like I should consider creating a custom `URLStreamHandler` to avoid temp jar issues, so I can ensure compatibility across different OS environments.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class loading dynamics**\\n\\nI'm trying to understand if it’s \\\"open-ended dynamic class loading.\\\" I don't think so. An active class path substring might require some specific handling. I can create a URL for the memory location of the manifest file, but I'm dealing with a situation where the Java URL constructor has an unknown protocol. This leads me to question whether using a custom URL handler is the way to go. Maybe adding anonymous classes in the test file could work, even if there's no explicit mapping. I wonder if it's better to stick with a real jar URL for more behavioral accuracy.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Writing manifest data**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how I can write the manifest to bytes using `Manifest.write()` and a `ByteArrayOutputStream`. It seems like a straightforward way to handle manifest data, and I like the idea of converting it into a byte array. This approach should allow me to easily manipulate or store the manifest information as needed. It’s great to have this clear method to work with, making my task feel more manageable!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating resource inclusion**\\n\\nI need to consider including the test resource path in Native. When the context class loader uses getResourceAsStream with a class resource, the agent will include the resource. During a native run, if the resource isn't included, it could throw a RuntimeException from the active class. Forge agent merging should cover this, but if the dynamic-access call site only gets tested when `read()` is executed, it calls input.read. So, I think we might not need direct reflection here.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Added a dedicated Scala test for the active dynamic-access class:\n\n- `tests/src/org.scala-lang/scala-reflect/2.11.8/src/test/scala/org_scala_lang/scala_reflect/ManifestResourcesAnonymous3Test.scala`\n\nThe test creates a manifest-backed archive entry for the test class resource via `ZipArchive.fromManifestURL`, sets the context class loader, opens the manifest resource entry, and calls `InputStream.read()` to exercise:\n\n- `scala.reflect.io.ManifestResources$$anon$3.read`\n- `ClassLoader#getResourceAsStream(String)`\n\nI did not run tests, per instructions.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0c458bdbb7bc74a90169fa4e643a54819fa0078787e6d83c99\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 649, "output": 1493, "cacheRead": 25088, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 27230, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1778011726281, "responseId": "resp_0c458bdbb7bc74a90169fa4e4efe90819fb8bdb80ba6bfef2b"}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating manifest entries**\n\nI'm thinking about whether manifest entries should use insertion ordering for keys. I don’t think that’s necessary. Then, I wonder if a manifest entry with a name longer than 70 bytes could be wrapped. But I believe `Manifest.write` handles that appropriately. It looks like it’s all fine in the end! Keeping track of these details is important for functionality, so I'm glad I checked on this.\n\n**Evaluating stream handling in Java**\n\nI’m thinking about issues with cache and file deletion on Windows potentially failing because of an open jar file. It seems that the test environment is likely Linux, which complicates things. Using `new Manifest(input)` might read the stream but doesn't close it afterwards. This can lead to source leaks, especially since the stream isn't closed in `ManifestResources.iterator`. It seems like I should consider creating a custom `URLStreamHandler` to avoid temp jar issues, so I can ensure compatibility across different OS environments.\n\n**Exploring class loading dynamics**\n\nI'm trying to understand if it’s \"open-ended dynamic class loading.\" I don't think so. An active class path substring might require some specific handling. I can create a URL for the memory location of the manifest file, but I'm dealing with a situation where the Java URL constructor has an unknown protocol. This leads me to question whether using a custom URL handler is the way to go. Maybe adding anonymous classes in the test file could work, even if there's no explicit mapping. I wonder if it's better to stick with a real jar URL for more behavioral accuracy.\n\n**Writing manifest data**\n\nI’m thinking about how I can write the manifest to bytes using `Manifest.write()` and a `ByteArrayOutputStream`. It seems like a straightforward way to handle manifest data, and I like the idea of converting it into a byte array. This approach should allow me to easily manipulate or store the manifest information as needed. It’s great to have this clear method to work with, making my task feel more manageable!\n\n**Evaluating resource inclusion**\n\nI need to consider including the test resource path in Native. When the context class loader uses getResourceAsStream with a class resource, the agent will include the resource. During a native run, if the resource isn't included, it could throw a RuntimeException from the active class. Forge agent merging should cover this, but if the dynamic-access call site only gets tested when `read()` is executed, it calls input.read. So, I think we might not need direct reflection here.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0c458bdbb7bc74a90169fa4e4ffb54819f9baef7c90a2dde74\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp-k5k0Oq1zAKtugvbX5AnnrOHT-kzVlqnSFye7Hy7sG7UjmD-pOhWSdJH1S5lsJ9cDNXUaWlrzu4nyBcmsviRhkiPrjZsCfXL0UyVrqpWgbW8CJaMCCDxU7rUr6HVdxaG4qKfmIIn4sv-g9-u2AH7iHcgWduxiItsH3-l0QVvKCAANpug9phMnhWaLKnr4knTbUYY_k1Mi18MFj1-GsAC3PmAZ_fu6IoCJvwMkVXghWsB4So1O8wGbwXq7fWSPFnReHEbbUXaOqwQjQcukDEnk948ECYM_1mMOPAyH3prWXAw1Jkf2Oo-3n2V8pfuM-d5I9_x4LD_Fmy9yA6yDDR2viYUTcPdJm6wjf0IMGkrm54gNy4WvFC73bwqzffz2lzoWpxyKKqslH7aUjyGKp_LuqzyMwlUmH_y5IEG1wBE4s0aIftBkVo4LxGnkiAkJaQeYDSMvbtTEHXsHPesgSpXp4ncfxM-P8xpw51iJEapZOVtP979sBCewBKW_2OQZ-oypYF7fvBML_v_vD8y3dm6uM-O4qSFADYHt8YzK0n7ea20OEA2HAJZamilk3wMmayALEaIYWVwYe0wxPFegAp8EyW-XpMYFKmHD22kB0HfcREadvV7q14c40xMQDk7sRucaf5WnabllCNer3L1P_hGh4YkVQiNFkno62Mm4A1l5JJWozbhaiYoVg_o1KGYFS7PhGzZM3kaIsi-1V5MRvNqeyjthGFr23nLMkz0O0yvvbVBv2a9zBcibvCl_1KC0JR4M_ZdxowQMzAKZAemlE39e2fPrijSYDBQqTYv6zhRRJqKU35YEdDZU8G_Rj05oTnP9ZspYW30L5x__hQhR_i-86r7UNb8dtBDFIM-P7Zvj7HRgokgmJcDjz-2-NLece11kMeOFWX7yxiSf5hSlA8jFKsqYfq9ABMWQt6cxktpFl19kvYMQjitMxXM_KUCTRERgFjtE8hGRuY_c-8sus-iOSP2dYikWPRNi1u99A0w498WgtgK7VjEaqFC2U4mvzOwXiNFePVucnXnirkcXgm_AhCBtlkbcscPjYih5T8cFS7Va9lYB6LXjGEt1LAeIh2DRGteN0wvEVGHUK0YyZBKloud13UaVhEOQLn1dLR4KaILnnZJQZYltGSu9bMT9ZW